{{Taxobox | image = Notiothauma reedi.jpg | image_caption = ''Notiothauma reedi'' | fossil_range=[[Triassic]] - Recent | regnum = [[Animalia]] | phylum = [[Arthropoda]] | classis = [[Insecta]] | ordo = [[Mecoptera]] | familia = '''Eomeropidae''' | subdivision_ranks = [[genus|Genera]] | subdivision = * {{extinct}}''[[Eomerope]]'' * {{extinct}}''[[Jurathauma]]''<ref name=Zhang>Zhang J-X, Shih C-K, Petrulevičius JF, Ren D (2011) A new fossil eomeropid (Insecta, Mecoptera) from the Jiulongshan Formation, Inner Mongolia, China. Zoosystema 33(4): 443–450. doi: 10.5252/z2011n4a2</ref> * {{extinct}}''[[Tsuchingothauma]]'' * {{extinct}}''[[Thaumamerope]]'' * {{extinct}}''[[Typhothauma]]'' * ''Notiothauma'' }}
'''Eomeropidae''' is a [[family (biology)|family]] of aberrant, flattened [[scorpionflies]] represented today by [[extant taxon|only a single living species]], '''''Notiothauma reedi''''', known from the ''[[Nothofagus]]'' forests in southern [[Chile]], while all other recognized genera in the family are known only as fossils, with the earliest from Triassic-aged strata,<ref name=TsuTyp>{{cite journal|last1=Zhang Junxia |year=2011 |title=A new fossil eomeropid (Insecta, Mecoptera) from the Jiulongshan Formation, Inner Mongolia, China |journal=Zoosystema |volume=33 |issue=4 |pages=443–450|display-authors=etal}}</ref> and the youngest from Paleogene-aged strata.<ref name=TsuTyp /><ref name=Archibald>Archibald, S. Bruce, Alexandr P. Rasnitsyn, and Mikhail A. Akhmetiev. "Ecology and distribution of Cenozoic Eomeropidae (Mecoptera), and a new species of ''Eomerope'' Cockerell from the Early Eocene McAbee locality, British Columbia, Canada." Annals of the Entomological Society of America 98.4 (2005): 503-514.</ref>
==Genera== * {{extinct}}''[[Eomerope]]''. This genus is known from [[Paleogene]] fossils from [[Eocene]] and [[Oligocene]] strata of [[North America]], and Paleocene to Oligocene strata of [[Russia]].<ref name=Archibald /> Because ''N. reedi'' is not known in the fossil record, ''Eomerope'' is the youngest of the fossil genera, and has the widest range. * {{extinct}}''[[Jurachorista]]''. Known from the early Jurassic, Sinemurian, of Dorset England. * {{extinct}}''[[Jurathauma]]''. ''J. simplex'' is one of three species of eomeropid scorpionflies from the Middle Jurassic of China. Its wing veins are distinct from all other eomeropids.<ref name=Zhang /> * ''Notiothauma''. ''N. reedi'' is a remarkable species, flattened and extremely [[cockroach]]-like in appearance and habits. It is nocturnal, and scuttles on the forest floor, where it can be collected by laying trails of oatmeal. The larvae are still unknown. Because this is the last extant species of Eomeropidae, ''N. reedi'' can be characterized as a [[living fossil]] taxon.<ref name=Archibald /> * {{extinct}}''[[Thaumatomerope]]''. This genus is known from the Triassic-aged Madygen [[Lagerstätte]], of Ladinian to Carnian [[Kyrgyzstan]]. ''Thaumatomerope''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s placement is subjective, as it has also been placed within [[Meropeidae]], and in its own monotypic family, "Thaumatomeropidae." * {{extinct}}''[[Tsuchingothauma]]''. ''T. shihi'' is one of three species of eomeropid scorpionflies from the Middle Jurassic of China. Its fossils are found in two formations, one with ''Typhothauma'', and another with ''Jurathauma'' * {{extinct}}''[[Typhothauma]]''. ''T. yixianensis'' is one of three species of eomeropid scorpionflies from the Middle Jurassic of China.
