{{Refimprove|date=October 2012}}
'''Tache noire de la sclerotique''' ([[French language|French]] for ''Black spot of the sclera'') is one of the ocular signs of [[death]] in which a reddish-brown discoloration is transversely arranged across the [[sclera]]. It occurs when the eyes are not completely closed so that the sclera is exposed to air.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rF1WTiX0nHEC&pg=PA168 |title=Forensic Pathology for Police, Death Investigators, Attorneys, and Forensic ... - Joseph A. Prahlow - ßĘČ Google |publisher=Books.google.com.eg |date= |accessdate=2012-10-14}}</ref> If the eyelids are open for a few hours after death, a film of cell debris and mucus forms two yellow triangles on the sclera, each at side of the [[iris (anatomy)|iris]], with base towards the margin of [[cornea]] and apex towards medial or lateral [[canthus]] of the eye, which becomes brown and then black within a few hours, upon which dust settles and the surface becomes wrinkled.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Synopsis of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. - K.S. Narayan Reddy |publisher= Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers (P) Ltd. |website= www.jaypeebrothers.com}}</ref>

